  "relevant_summary": "Across studies of vegetation clearance, numbers of frog species increased or natterjack toad populations increased, stabilized or were maintained when clearance was combined with other habitat management (761). One before-and-after study reported that habitat management including vegetation clearance maintained a great crested newt population for the first six years but not in the longer term (761). A before-and-after study found increased occupancy by natterjack toads following vegetation clearance (761). For replanting, amphibian abundance or community composition was similar to natural sites following tree planting, or became more similar with time since grassland reseeding (849). After logging, amphibian abundance in planted forests with herbicide treatment was lower or similar to naturally regenerating forests depending on species and forest age (849). Amphibians colonized replanted forest, reseeded grassland and seeded/transplanted upland habitats, and wetlands within reseeded grasslands were used more frequently than those in farmland but less than those in natural grasslands (849).",
