{
  "query": "As an alternative to treating infected individuals, what environmental management actions can help control chytridiomycosis in the wild?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Adding salt to ponds: One study in Australia reported that after salt was added to a pond containing the chytrid fungus, a population of green and golden bell frogs remained free of chytridiomycosis for at least six months (Action ID: 762).\n- Removing the chytrid fungus from ponds: A before-and-after study in Mallorca found that pond drying combined with fungicidal treatment of resident midwife toads reduced infection levels but did not eradicate chytridiomycosis (Action ID: 766).\n- Increasing water/enclosure temperature: Across four of five studies in Australia, Switzerland, and the USA, raising enclosure or water temperatures to 30\u201337\u00b0C for over 16 hours cured frogs and toads of chytridiomycosis; one study found that 30\u201335\u00b0C for 36 hours did not cure northern leopard frogs (Action ID: 770).\n- Biosecurity via equipment sterilization: There is no direct evidence on effects of sterilizing equipment when moving between amphibian sites on disease spread; however, Virkon S disinfectant did not affect survival, mass, or behaviour of common frog/toad tadpoles or moor frog embryos/hatchlings, while bleach significantly reduced survival of common frog and common toad tadpoles (Action ID: 768).",
